    "   \"source\": [\n",
    "    \"from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"scaler = MinMaxScaler()\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"# Normalizing sqft_living to be between 0 and 1\\n\",\n",
    "    \"df['sqft_living_norm'] = scaler.fit_transform(df[['sqft_living']])\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"print(\\\"Normalization complete!\\\")\\n\",\n",
    "    \"df[['sqft_living', 'sqft_living_norm']].head()# FEATURE CONSTRUCTION: Creating house_age\\n\",\n",
    "    \"df['house_age'] = df['date'].dt.year - df['yr_built']\\n\",\n",
    "    \"print(\\\"Feature Construction Complete!\\\")\\n\",\n",
    "    \"df[['date', 'yr_built', 'house_age']].head()\"\n",
    "   ]\n",
    "  },\n",
    "  {\n",
    "   \"cell_type\": \"markdown\",\n",
    "   \"id\": \"2aa33ff5-e04d-4bcc-8ec9-1e903956d1c4\",\n",
    "   \"metadata\": {},\n",
    "   \"source\": [\n",
    "    \"1. Aggregation (The Summary)\\n\",\n",
    "    \"**Data Categorization**: We used groupby('grade') to calculate the average price for every quality level.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"Interpretation: This technique allows us to shift from looking at 21,613 individual houses to seeing the \\\"big picture\\\" of the market. By calculating the mean price for each grade, we can confirm a clear trend: as the construction quality (grade) increases, the market value rises exponentially. This summary is essential for identifying which house characteristics have the strongest influence on price across the entire King County area.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"2. Normalization (The Scaler)\\n\",\n",
    "    \"**Feature Scaling**: We used MinMaxScaler to change sqft_living into sqft_living_norm.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"Interpretation: We transformed the square footage values so they all fit within a strict range of 0 to 1. In the raw data, square footage is measured in thousands, while other features like \\\"floors\\\" are measured in single digits. Normalization ensures that the mathematical size of the numbers does not bias the model; it forces the computer to treat a large house and a small house on the same scale of importance during analysis.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"3. Feature Construction (The Builder)\\n\",\n",
    "    \"**Variable Derivation**: We created the house_age column by subtracting the year built from the sale year.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"Interpretation: This step involved creating a new, more predictive variable that didn't exist in the original CSV file. A raw year like \\\"1955\\\" is just a label, but \\\"59 years old\\\" is a measurement of time. By constructing house_age, we provide the model with a direct way to calculate how the Reduce redundant data and perform need-based discretization\\n\",\n",
    "    \"age of a property impacts its current depreciation or historical value.\"\n",
    "   ]\n",
    "  },\n",
    "  {\n",
    "   \"cell_type\": \"code\",\n",
    "   \"execution_count\": 37,\n",
    "   \"id\": \"dcb80e93-64bc-4f8c-b0a0-b3d639ad5af6\",\n",
    "   \"metadata\": {},\n",
    "   \"outputs\": [\n",
    "    {\n",
    "     \"name\": \"stdout\",\n",
    "     \"output_type\": \"stream\",\n",
    "     \"text\": [\n",
    "      \"Transformations Complete!\\n\"\n",
    "     ]\n",
    "    }\n",
    "   ],\n",
    "   \"source\": [\n",
    "    \"import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\\n\",\n",
    "    \"import seaborn as sns\\n\",\n",
    "    \"from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"# A. AGGREGATION: Summary Table\\n\",\n",
    "    \"agg_df = df.groupby('grade')['price'].mean().reset_index()\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"# B. NORMALIZATION: Scaling sqft_living to (0, 1)\\n\",\n",
    "    \"scaler = MinMaxScaler()\\n\",\n",
    "    \"df['sqft_living_norm'] = scaler.fit_transform(df[['sqft_living']])\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"# C. FEATURE CONSTRUCTION: Creating house_age\\n\",\n",
    "    \"df['house_age'] = df['date'].dt.year - df['yr_built']\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"print(\\\"Transformations Complete!\\\")\"\n",
    "   ]\n",
    "  },\n",
    "  {\n",
    "   \"cell_type\": \"code\",\n",
    "   \"execution_count\": 47,\n",
    "   \"id\": \"47fe501a-e2b0-4cda-b754-43fdea0dfb08\",\n",
    "   \"metadata\": {\n",
    "    \"scrolled\": true\n",
    "   },\n",
    "   \"outputs\": [\n",
    "    {\n",
    "     \"data\": {\n",
    "      \"image/png\": \"\",\n",
    "      \"text/plain\": [\n",
    "       \"<Figure size 1800x500 with 3 Axes>\"\n",
    "      ]\n",
    "     },\n",
    "     \"metadata\": {},\n",
    "     \"output_type\": \"display_data\"\n",
    "    }\n",
    "   ],\n",
    "   \"source\": [\n",
    "    \"fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(18, 5))\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"# Trend 1: Distribution of House Age (Constructed Feature)\\n\",\n",
    "    \"sns.histplot(df['house_age'], bins=30, kde=True, ax=axes[0], color='orange')\\n\",\n",
    "    \"axes[0].set_title('Trend: Property Age Distribution')\\n\",\n",
    "    \"axes[0].set_xlabel('Years Old')\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"# Trend 2: Normalized Square Footage (Scaled Feature)\\n\",\n",
    "    \"sns.histplot(df['sqft_living_norm'], bins=30, kde=True, ax=axes[1], color='green')\\n\",\n",
    "    \"axes[1].set_title('Trend: Scaled Living Area (0 to 1)')\\n\",\n",
    "    \"axes[1].set_xlabel('Normalized Sqft')\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"# Trend 3: Average Price by Grade (Aggregated Trend)\\n\",\n",
    "    \"sns.barplot(data=agg_df, x='grade', y='price', hue='grade', legend=False, ax=axes[2], palette='magma')\\n\",\n",
    "    \"axes[2].set_title('Trend: Price Growth by Quality Grade')\\n\",\n",
    "    \"axes[2].set_ylabel('Mean Price')\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"plt.tight_layout()\\n\",\n",
    "    \"plt.show()\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\"\n",
    "   ]\n",
    "  },\n",
    "  {\n",
    "   \"cell_type\": \"markdown\",\n",
    "   \"id\": \"b03a4aa2-99ae-451b-8652-3d266e1411b3\",\n",
    "   \"metadata\": {},\n",
    "   \"source\": [\n",
    "    \"**1.Trend: Property Age Distribution (Histogram)**\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"The Trend: The orange histogram shows that the housing stock isn't evenly distributed. There are massive \\\"spikes\\\" around the 10–20 year and 60+ year marks.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \" This indicates that King County experienced specific \\\"building booms.\\\" For this project, this suggests that the market is divided between mid-century \\\"classic\\\" homes and newer modern developments, with very little in between.\\n\",\n",
    "    \" \\n\",\n",
    "    \"Interpretation: This distribution analysis reveals the historical development cycles within the King County housing market. The multi-modal nature of the histogram characterized by several distinct peaks indicates specific eras of high-volume construction. By analyzing these frequency clusters, we can identify which decades dominate the current inventory, providing essential context for how property age might influence overall market depreciation.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"**2.Trend: Scaled Living Area (Histogram)**\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"The Trend: The green histogram is heavily Right-Skewed. Almost all the data is bunched up between 0.0 and 0.3 on  normalized scale.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"This confirms that the \\\"typical\\\" home in  dataset is small-to-medium sized. The very long, thin tail on the right represents \\\"Outliers\\\" (massive mansions). This trend tells you that a standard model will work for most houses, but  might need a special approach for high-square-footage estates.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"Interpretation: By applying feature scaling to the living area measurements, we standardized the data to a 0-1 range, allowing for a clearer view of property density. The resulting histogram shows a significant 'right-skew,' confirming that the vast majority of market activity is concentrated in small-to-mid-sized residential units. The thin 'tail' on the right represents rare, high-square-footage outliers, which helps prioritize the model's focus on the most common home sizes.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"**3.Trend: Price Growth by Quality Grade (Bar Chart)**\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"The Trend: The purple bar chart shows a J-Curve (Exponential growth). Prices rise slowly from Grade 3 to 8, but they skyrocket once you hit Grade 10, 11, and 12.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"This is your most important discovery. It proves that Quality (Grade) is not a linear predictor. A one-point increase in grade at the low end adds a little value, but a one-point increase at the high end adds millions of dollars.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"Interpretation: Through data aggregation, we established a clear correlation between construction quality and market value. This visualization highlights an exponential pricing trend: while value increases incrementally across mid-tier grades (5–8), there is a dramatic surge in mean price as properties reach 'Luxury' classifications (11–13). This confirms that architectural grade is a non-linear driver of price, making it one of the most critical variables for accurate valuation.\"\n",
    "   ]\n",
    "  },\n",
